    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="187"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 4277.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Minister <persName type="to">Rockhill</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Departmment of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-02-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 247.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 482 of December 18 last,<note n="a" xml:id="d187fna">See <ref
                            target="frus1906p1#pg_290">Foreign Relations, 1906, p. 290</ref>.</note>
                    inclosing a memorandum prepared by Mr. Williams, Chinese secretary of the
                    legation, on the subject of the foreign settlements at the open ports of China,
                    which notes the facts that mark the stages of the movement of the Chinese to
                    narrow the privileges of foreign residents at these ports.</p>
                <p>The Government of the United States is determined in its opposition to the
                    abridgment of rights now enjoyed by foreigners in the settlements or concessions
                    already established or to be enjoyed by them in settlements or concessions to be
                    hereafter established.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Bacon.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
